author: nick.ghita
content:
I've been working on updating trin's bridge for post-merge data and looking for some feedback on an idea...

Initially the plan was to maintain an `era1` bridge for pre-merge, an `era` bridge for post-merge (non-ephemeral) and then a `latest` bridge for ephemeral. 

However, `era` files don't have receipts, so we could either use a live provider (which has mixed performance in terms of being able to deliver those receipts) or we define a new `era` format that contains the receipts. It seems like the best option here is to define a new `era` format.

Ok, so if we have to define a new `era` format, then maybe we can define this format to be compatible pre & post merge, by updating `Header` to be `HeaderWithProof` 

Pros:
- we have a single era file format for all non-ephemeral history data
- the bridge can be relatively "dumb" and just gossip the deserialized content without having to generate proofs on-the-fly, which involves some overhead based on the height. 

Cons: 
- the height-based proof generation overhead moves into the tooling that generates these files, but now the proof-generation only has to happen once when you're creating the file, rather than on-the-fly every time you want to gossip a particular epoch
- we'll have to maintain some architecture that generates/uploads a public endpoint to access these files for each new epoch (a la `https://mainnet.era.nimbus.team/`) but that'll be required regardless
- work required to regenerate pre-merge files in the new format, but this only needs to happen once

maybe the only concern I can think of is that the new era files will be based on a portal-defined type, rather than more "established" native ethereum types. so, let's say we want to change `HeaderWithProof` at some point in the future, we will have to re-generate all of the files.
